demand: About taking decisions that involve you and also other people and how you act towards other people.
comment: I think it was a bit slow, it would have been better if it didn't take that much time between the periods to give it a bit of emotion and involvement in it

demand: Someone's habits/views on dividing money fairly based on other's political views?
comment: Slightly tedious, repetitive, obvious that if everyone's fair when dividing more likely to get more money

demand: The experiment was about the link between our political ideas and how much we'd give to those around us in comparison to ourselves
comment: It was okay, it felt unfair at points because I was always shown as the 'most right wing' on the scale however i only put myself at a 6 - slightly right wing. Many people gave me less because of that, thought I think that it should just be equal no matter what politic really
degree: BA History of Art & English Literature

demand: In my opinion, it was about how people with different political views can find a deal that suits everyone of them personally
comment: The experiment was good and very interesting too

demand: Peoples attitudes towards wealth equality in regards to political preferences and race.
comment: It was a very interesting and insightful test.

demand: I think the experiment was about how far people are willing to go in order to be a part of a group. Once a person was close to another person in political views
comment: I enjoyed this experiment, it was simple to understand, and was also quite interesting to see how people divided money into 3 when they had the information about a persons political views. Once a person was closer to another person in the graph that was displayed, the pattern that I noticed was that when one had to choose who would get the extra few pennies, one would choose the person that had the closest political views as yourself.

demand: If one person is influenced by the race and political views of another in distributing out wealth.
comment: I hope no one was influenced by such factors in sharing the money, makes me quite uncomfortable.

demand: Whether individuals who are more left are more likely to distribute money equally and whether race and gender had any influence. So controlling for, gender, ethnicity and political sway.
comment: Good, though it took a long time for some people to answer.

demand: I believed the purpose of the experiment was to determine how political alignment (and through that economic viewpoint) affected your choice of division of money, and how your perception of others political/economic views had an effect on that decision.
comment: Good experiment, as it provided a clearer understanding (in my own eyes) of how political views seem to affect economic standpoints.

demand: How people divide money and how they perceive race/gender and political orientation
comment: Very well structured and provided a variety of different situations

demand: How much money you are willing to split with someone based on their race, gender (from the avatar) and general political standpoint (from the slider).
comment: It was a good experiment, if a little confusing at first. I enjoyed participating.

demand:
Fairness, racism, sexism.
How ethnicity and gender influences one's decision.
The allocation of money represents one's view and values on other people.
Democracy in regulating greed and a hint of is there a political/racial bias even there
comment: It was fun. There is a difference between brute logic, and human logic which contains psychological, social, etc. biases. I like computers better.

demand: how people's decisions are affected by political ideologies, by gender and ethnicity
How would peoples decisions affect yours and vice versa.
comment: interesting at how some people would choose to only maximise their own winnings but others divided it near enough equally to ensure that other people will accept the offer

demand: Odds and Chances. Essentially finding out whether greed overcame common sense when it came to money. If people chose to heavily prioritise their own 'slice of the pie' then chances are it would be rejected, meaning that the overall amount for everyone, including themselves, would be much less.
comment: Fairly fun, was interesting to see if greed overcame common sense. It's a shame it took some people so long to continue everytime.

demand: the experiment was about understanding how people think when they are asked to divide money between groups and if how the result(money) affect the decisions we take
comment: It was quite easy, and a bit tricky as i was trying to make the correct decision of the how the amount was divided

demand: I imagine this experiment was about the idea of how people decide wealth will be distributed, how this is factored in regarding gender, race and political ideology. Another important factor is the amount of social cohesion and that is created by the establishments of economic paradigms. Will people accept what they view as unfair treatment if objecting causes a larger economic loss?
comment: For the most part, the subjects I interacted with wished to keep finances equally distributed, although there were some discrepancies in how evenly. I only had one experience where I felt a subject allocated too much to himself but it wasn't enough to warrant a rejection. If I had seen it happen a second time, however, I would have rejected. If the funds distributed are largely fair, even with a small amount withheld to one party will ultimately be outvoted.
